According to “Box Office Mojo” on September 7, 2020, Tenet grossed $20 million during the Labor Day weekend in the US (https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1442940417/weekend/), whereas Forbes.com reported a figure of $20.2 million (https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2020/09/07/box-office-movies-tenet-chris-nolan-150m-robert-pattinson-john-david-washington-dunkirk-interstellar-inception/#4760309c3885), including whatever it made in Canada in the seven prior days. Considering that the Labor Day weekend was the film’s inaugural weekend, of its weekend’s performance, and that 65% of U.S. movie theaters were opened (https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-tenet-opens-to-20m-as-u-s-theaters-reopen-nears-150m-globally), with limitation, it cannot be expected that the figure for revenue, for that weekend reported as of September 8th will be above $100 million.

Domestic box office sales usually account for 40% of a movie's box office gross. Given that the international box office gross for Tenet is $53.6 mil, under normal circumstances we would expect the film to gross $35.7 mil domestically. Christopher Nolan's last three films all grossed over $50 mil (with the highest grossing $62.8 mil) on their opening weekend showing on approximately 3700 screens. Given that tenet will show on only 2000 screens and theaters are only allowing about 50% capacity, we could expect about 1/4 of the domestic gross of his previous movies, or about $13 million. However, early screenings could make up for some of the lost revenue. Likely, Tenet with gross somewhere between $13 mil and $35.7 mil.

BoxOfficeMojo so far shows no domestic grosses, which makes the site appear slow. So far UK has raked the highest gross: 7,123,704 USD (as of 04 September 2020, probably; since 28 August 2020), followed by France: 6,800,000 USD and South Korea: 5,100,000 USD (both since 26 August 2020) combined ~19mn USD. Population-wise these three countries combined are about 60% of the US total. If you could compare them by lifestyle, price level/purchase power and leisure behavior, then this indicates that Tenet might gross 30 to 35mn USD domestically for about the same time span of about 6 days.

Question and current situation: Tenet movie has $53,600,000 boxoffice gross for worlwide data as the film is not released yet in the US (release date Sep 3, 2020). On Mojo [1], "Domestic" refers to gross box-office revenue from North America (U.S., Canada, and Puerto Rico), "International" covers the rest of the world. The objective of the questions is to estimate the total domestic box office gross for Tenet as of 8 September 2020, according to Box Office Mojo? So 5 days domestic box office. My strategy is 1/ to have first an outside view looking at historical data for similar movies (Nolan previous movies for instance) to get the average domestic gross in the first 5 days after release. Previous Nolan movie in US Inception with release date July 15, 2010 (EMEA, APAC) has a domestic gross for the 5 first days (given it was out on Friday 16th-> we effect) of + 83 million [2] Interstellar released on November 5, 2014 (EMEA, Domestic) $49,661,813 [3] 2/ Regress from Europe to get insight on how this specific movie is performing. Chris Nolan's Tenet is off to a very solid start, topping all 41 overseas territories in which it opens, provided it indeed gets the post-opening legs that Warner Bros. is banking upon for global box office success. In normal times, a $53 million overseas launch (including $5 million in IMAX) for a film as big as Chris Nolan’s Tenet would be, at the very least, somewhat disappointing. 3/ consider the labor day factor here At this outside view stage I will have 40% > 80 million and 60% < 80 million.

We derive a base rate using the 5 day box office opening across multiple different countries adjusted for population and wealth from https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt6723592/. We then average the rates across each derived rate from each country (example: If canada is x the size of US, then we would take the box office results from canada and divide by x, then multiply by an adjustment factor via the average median income). I did this for the top countries to arrive at a base rate within the range of roughly 30-50 MM, which puts me solidly within my described range.

According to Box Mojo data, Christopher Nolan's movies' box office break down has an average of 30% domestic, 70% international. Tenet has been debut for the international audience for about one week and earned $55m international box office in total (data as of 9/3/2020). Without considering the coronavirus situation, since we are five days until the 9/8 deadline, the expected domestic box office is 55 * 5 /7 = $40m. On Sep 3rd, my expected movie theater capacity is at most 50% because of the hard coronavirus in-door activity limit. Besides, the biggest movie theater chains in the U.S. were acting in about 30% capacity on August 20th, which serves as a bottom line (https://www.cnbc.com/2020/08/20/coronavirus-amc-regal-and-cinemark-prepare-to-reopen-in-the-us-after-five-month-shutdown.html). Thus, the expected domestic box office is then $40*30% to $40*50%, which gives me 12m to 20m. I left a 1% margin in the bins below and above 1-80m margin for special scenarios, such as a sudden shut-down of all movie theaters/Tenet was much more welcomed by the American audience than the international ones.

https://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdown/sd977073668/ other Christopher Nolan movies have grossed around $50 million on the opening weekend, whereas this challenge extends two more days. I also noted that movie sales on Mondays and Tuesdays are likely to be much lower than weekends, meaning the additional two days may not add much

Comparable Nolan movies have all grossed less than 160 million during the first weekend. Furthermore, I found that international box office tends to account for ~1/2 - 2/3 of total revenue in high grossing movies. After grossing 50 million internationally, I do not expect Tenet to break that mark domestically given US' covid-19 situation which is relatively worse than most countries, small population relative to the rest of the world (1.5 billion total English speakers if you use that as a rough proxy of potentially interested moviegoers), and lack of theaters open, as Zach cited. A counterpoint to this is that the reviews for the movie are quite good (though not stellar by Nolan's standards) so I do not count out the minute chance that Americans make it out to see the movie.

Given that Tenet released in US theaters today (9/3), there is little reason to believe that it will gross less than $1 million, considering that the top movies for the last three weeks have all grossed greater than that. As for the upper bound, we can look at Christopher Nolan's previous three original movies. Inception, Inception, Interstellar, and Dunkirk have had $82.6m, $61.8m, and $64.3m as their opening 5-day domestic grosses (data from Box Office Mojo). However, obviously COVID has drastically reduced sales expectations, with only 62% of theaters open and all with social distancing in place. Additionally, the fact that more than half of Americans are extremely unlikely to go to a movie theater a month after they reopen, makes it seem extremely unlikely that Tenet will exceed $80 million (https://fortune.com/2020/09/03/tenet-us-movie-theaters-box-office-coronavirus-pandemic-release/). This lines up with analysts' forecast of about $25-35 million in opening week sales (https://www.boxofficepro.com/long-range-box-office-forecast-christopher-nolans-tenet/). If opening weekend sales are drastically higher than expected, I could adjust this forecast before the deadline.

Several factors / benchmarks to consider here when establishing / adjusting a prior, where we're primarily focused on calculating the tail risk of gross falling outside the $1mm-$80mm bin:

I believe that much of the demand for Christopher Nolan's movies (especially when first released) is driven by people knowing they're directed by Nolan. So, looking at initial box office revenue for prior Christopher Nolan's movies is a good starting point for determining demand for Tenet.
First forecast is done without doing any "specific" or "rigorous" data analysis techniques but rather from taking a holistic view at the question and the data we have so far.

We observed two Christopher Nolan movies, Dunkirk and Inception, noting that Inception was more successful. Given that currently 1 week after international release, the movie has grossed ~$57 million, we strongly believe that box office revenues will be in the $1 million to $80 million bucket. Dunkirk grossed $64 million in the first 5 days, while Inception grossed $82 million. Both of these movies released in pre-Covid America and were fairly recent. Thus $80 million seems like a very strong upper bound for Tenet's box office earnings. Tenet is opening in 80% of American theaters to begin with, and many of these will have social distancing restrictions, which will limit seating and demand.

The greatest risk is that the movie will be further delayed. However, considering the proximity to September 8th, this is highly unlikely.

The movie releases on Sept 3, giving it only 5 days to accrue revenue. Christopher Nolan's last movie (Dunkirk, 2017) had domestic opening-week gross of $74.7mm, while Interstellar (2014) had domestic opening week gross of $66mm. These net out to approximately $20k and $19k per theater respectively. AMC announced it is opening about 70% of movie theaters for release of Tenet. Some of these movie theaters (NJ, California) must open at 25% capacity, while theaters in populous states such as NY will not even open. If we make optimistic assumptions: average $20k per theater (same as Dunkirk, with what will likely be much less capacity), approximately 70% of theaters open (of which we assume 75% are operating at same capacities as in 2017), this gives us a revenue projection of $42mm. It is hard to envision the movie being such a flop as to have less than $1mm revenue; instead, this should represent probability of movie being delayed even further. This close to release (tomorrow!), this is extremely unlikely.

In order to have a base case of how movies are performing right now, I looked at the top 5 highest grossing domestic films in August 2020. As a side note, Tenet is expected to debut on September 3rd in about 3,000 theaters domestically (source: https://www.indiewire.com/2020/07/tenet-opens-september-3-theaters-future-1234576434/ ). Of the top 5, only Unhinged and The New Mutants (TNM) are apt comparisons to Tenet since they had larger debuts of several thousand theaters. Furthermore, Unhinged is a rather noisy estimate of how much theaters are making on films nowadays since it had an initial limited debut followed by a wider debut of around 2,000 theaters. Thus, we will focus on using TNM as the base case.

Tenet has been average ~$2000 per screen in overseas markets [1]. Tenet is expected to open on ~2000 screens in the US on September 3. [2]

As of August 31, Tenent has already earned $53MM and ranks #9 for 2020 in the worldwide box office, prior to the US launch. Due to minimal competition, Tenent also will likely have a lengthy run. In 2020, gross is about 70% - 80% of total. Most recently, The New Mutants, an action horror sci-fi was released in theaters and earned $7MM opening weekend. With a similar genre, and more excitement around the film due to cast, director, and budget, we can expect Tenent to perform much higher. In 2017, Christopher Nolan’s Dunkirk earned $188MM gross in the box office. With Americans hungry for things to do, ready for new movies, and theaters opening up, we can expect Tenent to perform much higher than The New Mutants, though not as high as it would have pre-pandemic as many are still staying home.

Minor adjustments on priors. Shifting weight slightly from upper three brackets to lowest bracket. Underlying logic still generally consistent with original:

The trailer was released without a release date, making it more likely that it is delayed (~35%, my guess). However, August 14 looks like another option if it is delayed [1]. Given an August 14th release, I'd expect it to almost certainly gross below $80 million, possibly even under $1 million, though unlikely (~90% > 1 million). If we assume the August 14 date is fifty-fifty given a delay, with the other option being after Sept. 8, then the < 1 million probability becomes 20%. In the event of a July 17 release (~65%), then I'd say there's a 100% chance it exceeds $1 million, and there's a possibility that it exceeds $80 million, but I find this unlikely. However, a lot can change in 2-4 months so I'll bump up my estimate of above 80 to about 10% (given July 17 release). Therefore, greater than 80 has roughly 7%. I give 1% to 160-240 only because I think about how poorly I would've predicted today's events three and a half months ago.

Relative to the crowd, I think that >80 million is not that unrealistic, despite the most likely outcome being <80 million. Dunkirk made ~ 80 million domestic in about 1 week. Assuming they stick to the Jul 17 release date, that gives Tenet more than 1 month to do what Dunkirk did in one week — seems like theaters filling at 25% capacity is not too out of the question and Tenet won't be competing with anything. We don't have data on how willing people are to go to the theater, so I'm totally in the dark about that component. But I am somewhat optimistic about them sticking to the Jul 17 date. The website and twitter say so, Nolan seems to really want a theatrical release, and even if it gets pushed a month that still gives it time to make some money. I assign a significantly higher probability to the higher gross amounts (>160 million) than the crowd because I just don't know how consumer's willingness to go out and see a movie will change over the next few months. It seems unlikely, but if Tenet receives excellent press, is viewed as the only entertainment available, and theaters do a good job rolling out social distancing measures, it might be plausible that it does big numbers. We're simply bad at knowing how COVID and consumer behavior will progress more than 1 month out, so we should be more uncertain!

If there won't be an audience to watch the movie due to closed cinemas or lack of people going to cinemas, I assume they'll reschedule. It does not make sense to release the movie if you don't have the chance of people watching it. The production costs are 205 million, assuming marketing costs not included [1]. It's just not financially viable and I can't imagine how it could be, even if more and more people are starting to go watch movies in cinemas again.

People will become restless during extended lockdowns, which will result in a rebound in willingness to both a) risk catching covid in context of controlled outbreaks (similar to current situation in Australia for example) and b) spend money on attending cinema due to restrictions. Overall I expect this to mean a strong box office result slightly below the average of Interstellar and Inception ($240 million).

Two similar Christopher Nolan movies, Interstellar and Inception, grossed $188m and $292m, respectively [1]. Taking the average gives $240m best estimate in the absence of COVID. I revised this down slightly to $210m for the US market given it reputedly has a very long runtime.

Historic references (to arrive at a non-COVID base rate) are gross numbers for Dunkirk and Inception, both by Nolan, which were $183MM and $279MM, respectively. (Eight week period following same opening weekend in July) I simply averaged the two.
